Step 1: Download Node.js

Open any web browser.

Visit the official Node.js website: https://nodejs.org

On the homepage, you will see two versions:

LTS (Long Term Support) – Recommended version

Current – Latest features version

Click on the LTS version to download the Windows Installer (.msi file).

Step 2: Install Node.js

Locate the downloaded .msi file and double-click to open it.

Click Next in the setup wizard.

Accept the License Agreement and click Next.

Choose the destination folder (default location is recommended) and click Next.

Click Next again to confirm the default settings.

Click Install to begin the installation process.

Wait for the installation to complete.

Click Finish to close the setup wizard.

Step 3: Verify Installation

Press Windows + R, type cmd, and press Enter to open Command Prompt.

To check if Node.js is installed, type:

node -v

If installed successfully, it will display the Node.js version.

To check npm (Node Package Manager), type:

npm -v

It will display the npm version.

Step 4: Test Node.js

In Command Prompt, type:

node

If the installation is successful, you will see a prompt symbol (>).

Type the following command:

console.log("Hello World")

Press Enter. The output will display:

Hello World

To exit from Node.js, type:

.exit
